<TITLE> Indices surge on govt plans to offload shares </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 27 (bdnews24.com)  The country's stock exchanges saw surges in indices Wednesday on news of government plans to offload 25 percent stakes in four companiesOsmania Glass Sheet, Atlas Bangladesh, National Tubes and Eastern Cables. Barring Osmania Glass, all witnessed increases in share price and appeared on the turnover board which analysts termed unnatural. An official of a brokerage house told bdnews24.com: "Investors are simply being irrational. How on earth can share price of an issue rise when supply is being increased?" It is very unfortunate that the investors behave like this, he added. Dhaka stocks maintained an upward curve in the general index throughout the day, at point rising 110 points above the previous day's closing mark, before declining slightly to finish high. DSE chief executive Salahuddin Ahmed said that such high market volatility harmed investors in the long run. The benchmark DGEN or general index closed 92.19 points, or 3.27 percent, up to 2906.80. The DSI or all share price index surged to 2456.10, up 70.72 points, or 2.96 percent from the previous day. The DSE-20 blue-chip index advanced 49.48 points, or 2.18 percent, to end on 2312.75. Turnover on the Dhaka Stock Exchange rose slightly to Tk 1.86 billion, from 10,517,432 traded shares, up from Tuesday's Tk 1.74 billion. Gainers outnumbered losers 185 to 32, while 8 issues held steady. Banks, oil and state owned companies drove the day's trading. AB Bank continued to top the DSE's turnover board, closing 3.23 percent higher at Tk 3043.25. Meghna Petroleum followed, ending on Tk 305, up 12.92 percent. State-owned Jamuna Oil also rose 11.03 percent to end on Tk 306.80. IFIC Bank advanced 3.09 percent from that the previous day to finish at Tk 2847. Atlas Bangladesh appeared on the board with a whopping 17.41 percent increase in its share price on reports of government plans to offload 25 percent of its stake in the company. It ended on Tk 378.30. Among other scrips on the turnover board: Grameen Mutual Fund One, Uttara Bank, National Tubes and Eastern Cables advanced, while UCBL fell. Indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange also ended up with an increase in turnover of almost one hundred million taka. It amounted to Tk 374.46 million from 2,174,819 traded shares, up from Tk 279.51 million the previous day. The CSCX or selective category index rose 158.96 points, or 3.41 percent, to end on 4808.66. The CASPI or all share price index closed at 7508.87, surging 222.50 points, or 3.05 percent. The blue chip CSE-30 was up 147.73 points, or 2.24 percent, to end at 6717.10. bd
